				<p class="lessonText">Each type of music note is played for a different length. This is called its <span>note duration</span>.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson2/durations.jpg" alt="note types">
				<hr class="hr">
				
				<p class="lessonText">Whole notes have the longest duration.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson2/wholedur.jpg" alt="whole note">
				<hr class="hr">
				
				<p class="lessonText">Half notes have the second longest duration because, you guessed it, they're "half" of a whole note. Two half notes equal one whole note.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson2/halfdur.jpg" alt="half note">
				<hr class="hr">
				
				<p class="lessonText">Next comes quarter notes. Quarter notes equal one-fourth of a whole note. Two quarter notes equal one half note. Four quarter notes equal one whole note.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson2/quarterdur.jpg" alt="quarter note">
				<hr class="hr">
				
				<p class="lessonText">Next is an eighth note. Eighth notes, and any other note with a duration smaller than a quarter note's duration, have flags attached to them (<span>shown in red</span>). A flag cuts the notes duration in half.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson2/flag.jpg" alt="note flag">
				<p class="lessonText">Since an eighth note has one flag, it equals half the duration of a quarter note. So two eighth notes equal one quarter note.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson2/eighthdur.jpg" alt="eighth note">
				<hr class="hr">
				
				<p class="lessonText">A sixteenth note has two flags, which means its duration is halved again. Two sixteenth notes equal one eighth note, and four of them equal one quarter note.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson2/sixtdur.jpg" alt="sixteenth note">
				<hr class="hr">
				
				<p class="lessonText">There are notes that contain more flags, but they are not used as often.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson2/moreFlags.jpg" alt="multple note flags on a note">
				<hr class="hr">

				<p class="lessonText">Here is a comparison chart of the different types of notes and their </p>
				<img src="../images/lesson2/noteChart.jpg" alt="note duration chart">
				<hr class="hr">
				
				<p class="lessonText"><span>Rests</span> are symbols the indicate a period of silence in the music. Rests have the same exact durations as notes. There are whole rests, half rests, quarter rests, and so on.</p><br>
				<p class="lessonText">A whole rest looks like a little box descending from the fourth staff line.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson2/wholeRest.jpg" alt="whole rest">
				<p class="lessonText">A half rest is a box ascending from the middle staff line. The image shows two half rests because, like notes, two half rests equal one whole rest.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson2/halfRest.jpg" alt="half rest">
				<p class="lessonText">Here are what the quarter, eighth, and sixteenth rests look like. Notice that the eighth and sixteenth rests do have flags, but they look like little curls.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson2/otherRests.jpg" alt="other rests">
